<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="aa-section-turntable" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivation for a turntable</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        Visualize a turntable of radius <m>R</m> that is rotating with constant angular velocity <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>.
        As shown in <xref ref="aa-turntable-setup" text="type-global" /> below,
        <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> points perpendicular to the turntable and is directed out of the screen.
    </p>

    <p>
        We can apply a local Cartesian coordinate system to any given point on the turntable,
        and for visual simplicity, we will do below so for a point on the edge of the turntable.
        All the unit direction vectors discussed below have an implied subscript "rot"
        since they are attached to the turntable,
        which is a rotating reference frame.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-setup">
        <caption>
            View from above of a turntable of radius <m>R</m> rotating at constant angular velocity <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>.
            The unit direction vectors of a local Cartesian coordinate system fixed to the turntable are shown at a point on the edge of the turntable.
            Vector <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> shows the turntable's constant angular velocity.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/aa-turntable-setup.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above,
                with radius and unit direction vectors for a point on its edge.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Consider a point fixed to the edge of the turntable:
        <m>\hat{i}</m> points to the local right,
        <m>\hat{j}</m> points directly inward toward the center of the turntable,
        and <m>\hat{k}</m> points in the same direction as <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>.
        Therefore,
        we can write <m>\vec{\Omega} = \Omega \, \hat{k}</m>,
        where <m>\lambda</m> [<m>\text{rad}</m>] is the angular displacement and
        <m>\Omega = \dfrac{D \lambda}{Dt}</m> [<m>\text{rad} \, \text{s}^{-1}</m>]
        is the angular speed.
        By these definitions,
        during a period of time <m>\delta t</m>,
        the turntable rotates through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        Note that any point on the turntable can be produced simply by decreasing the value of <m>R</m>;
        more generally,
        any point on the same plane as the turntable can be produced simply by changing the value of <m>R</m>.
        Thus, the following derivations apply to any point in the plane of the turntable.
    </p>

    <p>
        Furthermore, note that any point above or below the turntable can be produced simply by "lifting"
        the unit direction vectors upward in the direction of <m>\vec{\Omega}</m>
        or "pushing" the unit direction vectors downward in the direction of <m>-\vec{\Omega}</m>,
        respectively, as this does not change their orientations.
        Thus, the following derivations apply to any point above or below the plane of the turntable.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <xi:include href="aa-section-turntable-subsection-i.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="aa-section-turntable-subsection-j.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="aa-section-turntable-subsection-k.ptx" />

</section>